Northeast Utilities's transmission investments have grown consistently over the years, but the company has recently reported stronger results in its regulated utility operations. Northeast last year agreed to merge with New England utility Nstar NST for $4.3 billion in stock to form what the companies called one of the biggest utilities in the U.S.

don't think they'll offer shelter when trouble arrives. However, sweeping
changes in the industry have added voltage to some companies'
prospects.

attempts to recover from customers up to $300 million of costs from closing
the Millstone nuclear complex.

A federal prosecutor
 said he will not
file criminal charges against managers of the Maine Yankee nuclear power
plant.

 it will
likely need an extra month to restart one of the three idled nuclear
reactors at its Millstone power plant.

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Appoints New CEO

Northeast Utilities
 named Michael G.
Morris chairman, chief executive officer and president, and charged him
with the challenging task of restoring the troubled utility to
profitability.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Appoints New CEO
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Maine Yankee Plant Will Close

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The owners of Maine Yankee

nuclear-power plant will vote this week to permanently close the troubled
facility after talks to sell it to Peco Energy broke down over the issue of
responsibility for future expenses.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Maine Yankee Plant Will Close
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Andrew
Bary

Amid the din, the unglamorous and economically sensitive cyclical stocks
have been clanking to new highs.

Headlines.Author: William M. Bulkeley
Headlines.Headline: Northeast to Get $25 Million

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 trustees and
officers agreed to pay $25 million to settle claims made by
shareholders.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast to Get $25 Million
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline:
Utilities Woo Customers
With 'Green' Ad Claims

PARAGRAPH.#text:
As people
 in parts of the U.S. begin
choosing electric suppliers the same way they now select long-distance
phone service, many utilities are marketing their power as environmentally
friendly.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Utilities Woo Customers
With 'Green' Ad Claims
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Can't Raise Rates

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 can't boost rates
to recover some $1 billion in costs tied to closing its Millstone nuclear
plant, Connecticut regulators ruled.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Can't Raise Rates
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline:
Plants Face Costly Repairs
To Fix Safety Problems

PARAGRAPH.#text:
An exercise
 in which nuclear plants
told regulators how they failed to meet the technical terms of their
licenses has revealed costly overall safety concerns for many nuclear
plants.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Plants Face Costly Repairs
To Fix Safety Problems
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Plant May Close Permanently

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Central Maine
 Power and other owners
of the Maine Yankee plant said they may close it permanently.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Plant May Close Permanently
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Northeast to Pay $650,000 Fine

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 will pay a
$650,000 civil fine imposed by federal regulators for lax controls at the
company's Connecticut Yankee nuclear power plant.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast to Pay $650,000 Fine
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Northeast Violated Credit Pact

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 said it violated
a credit agreement with banks and is negotiating new financing arrangements
with them and regulators.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Violated Credit Pact
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Robert O'Brien
Headlines.Headline:
Intel Leads a Tech-Stock Rally
While IBM Boosts Blue Chips

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Technology stocks
 snapped back from
their recent sell-off Wednesday, while blue-chip stocks finished narrowly
higher in their first full session after the Federal Reserve's rate
increase.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Intel Leads a Tech-Stock Rally
While IBM Boosts Blue Chips
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Towns Fear Power Deregulation

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Electricity deregulation
 is sending
shivers through local economies that are dependent on power facilities that
won't be able to compete against a new generation of gas-fired plants.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Towns Fear Power Deregulation
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast May Suspend Payout

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 management will
recommend that the board of trustees suspend the company's common dividend
of 25 cents a share as part an effort to save cash the utility needs to
face competition.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast May Suspend Payout
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities Wins Order

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 won a temporary
restraining order against a New Hampshire restructuring plan that the
electric company says would unfairly prevent it from recovering its past
investments and could force two of its units into bankruptcy.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities Wins Order
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Utilities Are Jostled by Ruling

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Debt of Northeast
 Utilities and its
units plummeted following a regulatory ruling that could push some of its
entities into bankruptcy court protection.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Utilities Are Jostled by Ruling
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Robert O'Brien
Headlines.Headline:
Stocks Close Modestly Higher
Lifted by Rail, High-Tech Issues

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Transportation and
 high-technology
stocks moved higher, lifting major averages, as stocks stemmed a
three-session sell-off.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Stocks Close Modestly Higher
Lifted by Rail, High-Tech Issues
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Utility Suit Seeks to Block Order

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 said it and three
of its subsidiaries filed suit against the New Hampshire Public Utilities
Commision, seeking to block a restructuring order that Northeast says will
hurt the company financially.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Utility Suit Seeks to Block Order
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Dana Milbank
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities Is Dealt Blow

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 was dealt a blow
by New Hampshire, which issued a deregulation plan that the utility has
said could force two of its largest units into bankruptcy-court
protection.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities Is Dealt Blow
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Utility CEO Will Retire Soon

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 said its chairman
and chief executive officer will take early retirement, as the firm faces
nuclear plant closings and financial pressures.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Utility CEO Will Retire Soon
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities Posts Loss

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 reported a
fourth-quarter loss of $76.4 million, or 60 cents a share, compared with
net income of $64.2 million, or 50 cents a share, a year earlier. The
company cited nuclear-power problems.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities Posts Loss
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Maine Yankee Gets Officer

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Michael B. Sellman
 was named chief
nuclear officer for Maine Yankee Atomic Power's nuclear power plant, which
is closed pending safety and operations reviews.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Maine Yankee Gets Officer
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Northeast Names New Officials

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities named
 Neil S.
"Buzz" Carns senior vice president and chief nuclear officer for its
Millstone nuclear plant in Waterford, Conn., which is closed pending safety
reviews. The company also named Michael H. Brothers to oversee efforts to
return the Millstone 3 reactor to service.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Names New Officials
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Northeast to Post Sizable Loss

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities said
 it expects
to report a significant loss for the fourth quarter because of continued
nuclear-plant problems, rising oil prices and weather woes.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast to Post Sizable Loss
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Deregulation Threatens Utility

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 said two of its
units could be forced to file for bankruptcy protection if New Hampshire
proceeds with a deregulation plan.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Deregulation Threatens Utility
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities May Be Sued

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 is likely to face
lawsuits from the minority owners of one of its shuttered Millstone nuclear
reactors. Among those who may sue to recover the costs of buying
replacement power is New England Electric System, the region's
second-largest utility behind Northeast.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities May Be Sued
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities Is Criticized

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities'
 management was
blasted for its poor nuclear-safety program in a review ordered by
Connecticut regulators. Some senior officials were called on to resign.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities Is Criticized
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Maine Yankee Faces Hurdles

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The U.S. Nuclear
 Regulatory
Commission has outlined certain steps that the Maine Yankee nuclear power
plant must take to reopen, and plant officials have agreed not to restart
operations without NRC approval.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Maine Yankee Faces Hurdles
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Audit Pans Northeast Dividend

PARAGRAPH.#text:
A consultant told
 Connecticut's
utility regulator that Northeast Utilities must consider eliminating its
dividend to meet debt payments and the costs of righting its nuclear-power
program.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Audit Pans Northeast Dividend
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Nuclear Plant to Shut Down

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Utility owners
 of the Connecticut
Yankee nuclear power plant said they will close the troubled reactor 11
years ahead of schedule.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Nuclear Plant to Shut Down
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Gerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast to Delay Reactors

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 is unlikely to
reopen any of its troubled Millstone nuclear reactors until the second half
of 1997, later than it previously had estimated, a utility official
said.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast to Delay Reactors
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Utility Is Rebuked on Layoffs

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The U.S.
 Labor Department said
Northeast Utilities was wrong to insist that laid-off employees promise not
to sue the company in order to receive severance payments.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Utility Is Rebuked on Layoffs
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities' Net Falls

PARAGRAPH.#text:

 third-quarter
earnings plunged as costs associated with the outages at two of its nuclear
facilities continued to mount.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities' Net Falls
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities Net Drops

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 said
third-quarter profit plunged 99% mainly due to continuing outages at its
nuclear-power plants.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities Net Drops
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline:
Bond Deals Probed
In South Florida

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The U.S.
 Federal Bureau of
Investigation and the Securities and Exchange Commission are conducting
broad inquiries into government and financial corruption in South Florida.
So far, the investigations have embroiled county commissioners and
prominent investment bankers.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Bond Deals Probed
In South Florida
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Robert O'Brien
Headlines.Headline:
Stock Prices Move Lower
As Bond Market Retreats

Stocks made a halting effort Thursday to rebound from this week's modest
declines, but more worries about how the apparent economic slowdown will
affect third-quarter earnings prevented the market from rallying.

Stock Prices Move Lower
As Bond Market Retreats

 that owns the
Connecticut Yankee nuclear-power plant said a permanent shutdown of the
facility "seems likely" after analyses showed that repairs wouldn't be
economically justified.

In Technology's Wake

Energy and health
 stocks have made
some large moves, but haven't received much attention because volatile and
trendy technology stocks have hogged both the glory and the infamy.

In Technology's Wake

 inspection team
found operators of the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant failed to test some
safety systems or to correct other longstanding problems. The findings will
likely lead to fines and other penalties, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
said.

 Service downgraded
about $2.4 billion in debt securities issued by Northeast Utilities and
some of its subsidiaries, citing continuing troubles at its Millstone
nuclearpower plant.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline:
Regulators, Trustees
Put Pressure on Head
Of Northeast Utilities

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities'
 Chairman and
Chief Executive Bernard M. Fox has seen New England's largest electric
company go from being one of the country's best-managed nuclear utilities
to one besieged by regulators. Trustees are now talking about replacing
him.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Regulators, Trustees
Put Pressure on Head
Of Northeast Utilities
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Larry Bauman
Headlines.Headline:
Stock Prices Close Flat
As Investors Await Data

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Stocks ended
 their string of
record-breaking sessions Thursday as investors decided to postpone
additional buying until after Friday's release of the September employment
report.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Stock Prices Close Flat
As Investors Await Data

New England Electric
 will shed most
of its power assets, in one of the first big breakups under
deregulation.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Operators of
 the Maine Yankee nuclear
power plant said the U.S. Justice Department will review whether to bring
criminal charges over allegations the plant misrepresented to regulators
the ability of its emergency core-cooling system.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: NRC Review Focuses on Maine Plant
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Northeast Utilities
 removed two
executives from their current jobs as part of a management shuffle aimed at
ending the costly outage of the company's Millstone nuclear plant.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Removes 2 Executives
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

 wire found severed at the
Maine Yankee nuclear-power plant was cut accidentally, a review by the
plant found.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Power Utilities Set To Compete

PARAGRAPH.#text:
New England
 Electric System became
the first Massachusetts utility to reach a proposed restructuring pact with
the state's attorney general as part of the state's plan to deregulate the
industry. Massachusetts plans to allow power companies to compete for
customers beginning in 1998, and the state hopes to reach similar
agreements soon with other large utilities.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Power Utilities Set To Compete
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Moody's Investors
 Service said it
placed under review for possible downgrade debt held by Northeast
Utilities. About $2 billion of securities is affected.

The Maine
 Yankee nuclear power plant
has returned to service, following a six-week outage for safety
reviews.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

 Regulatory
Commission proposed fining the owners of the Vermont Yankee nuclear power
plant $50,000 for failing to notice for 22 years that its safety procedures
in the event of an accident were inadequate.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: NRC May Fine Vermont Plant
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Northeast Fires Executive

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 dismissed its
second-highest-ranking executive, amid mounting problems with its nuclear
power plants, and said it is the subject of a second criminal probe.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Fires Executive
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: NRC Questions Utility

The U.S. Nuclear
 Regulatory
Commission asked Northeast Utilities why its license to operate the
Connecticut Yankee nuclear power plant shouldn't be "suspended, modified or
revoked" because of safety problems.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: NRC Questions Utility
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Northeast Utilities
 said its
Connecticut Yankee nuclear power plant would remain shut down for up to two
more months.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Nuclear Plant to Remain Offline
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Indies Are Losing Power Struggle

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Utility deregulation
 is stirring up
the world of the independent electric producers. As smaller nonutility
generators are pressured by utilities to lower their prices, they're
finding that new generation projects are becoming more difficult to
launch.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Indies Are Losing Power Struggle
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: NRC Finds Errors at Plant

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The Nuclear
 Regulatory Commission
found "apparent violations" of safety guidelines at the Connecticut Yankee
nuclear-power plant, a finding that may extend the shutdown of the
reactor.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: NRC Finds Errors at Plant
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

PARAGRAPH.#text:
An internal review
 by the U.S.
Nuclear Regulatory Commission has found agency officials were slow to act
on complaints filed by a whistle-blower at Northeast Utilities' Millstone
nuclear plant, and did so only after the whistle-blower filed public
petitions about refueling practices there.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: NRC Review Finds Fault
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Northeast Utilities Closes Plant

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 closed its
Connecticut Yankee nuclear plant after it failed a safety review. It is the
second New England nuclear plant closed recently, raising power-shortage
fears.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities Closes Plant
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Robert McGough
Headlines.Headline:
Fund Bets on Future
Of Great Bay's Plant

Leon Cooperman is

Advisors can make money from the ill-starred Seabrook nuclear plant by
owning 34% of Great Bay Power, which wound up with the rights to sell 12%
of the power generated by the nuclear-power plant.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Fund Bets on Future
Of Great Bay's Plant
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 told the U.S.
Nuclear Regulatory Commission that it had found 1,187 deficiencies at its
idled Millstone 3 nuclear-power plant, a 35% increase from a previous
tally.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Millstone 3 Plant Is Struggling
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Millstone Weighs on Northeast

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities
 is facing much
higher-than-expected costs from the shutdown of the Millstone reactors.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Millstone Weighs on Northeast
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Gary Putka
Headlines.Headline: Connecticut Blackouts Feared

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities said
 the chances
of a large-scale blackout in Connecticut this summer have risen as a result
of the Millstone nuclear power plant shutdown, but the odds of such an
occurrence are still slim.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Connecticut Blackouts Feared
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Safety Reviews Ordered at Plant

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Federal regulators have
 ordered new
safety reviews at Northeast Utilities' Millstone nuclear power plant,
further delaying its restart until at least September.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Safety Reviews Ordered at Plant
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Maine Yankee Finds Problems

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The operators
 of the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant said an
internal review found "technical violations" of regulations that could lead to penalties by the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Maine Yankee Finds Problems
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Utility Gets Downgraded

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Moody's and
 Standard & Poor's lowered their ratings on the debt
of Northeast Utilities.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Utility Gets Downgraded
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Utilities Use Emergency Steps

Several utilities
 invoked emergency measures and urged customers to
conserve electricity as a heat wave sharply boosted demand in the East.

Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The U.S. Nuclear
 Regulatory Commission questioned safety assurances
provided by the Connecticut Yankee power plant, raising chances the plant could be shut down and
adding to the problems of Northeast Utilities, its main shareholder.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: NRC Questions Assurances
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The New Hampshire
 Supreme Court upheld a ruling by state regulators
that could allow electric utilities to compete in each other's service territories, another step in this state's
efforts to deregulate the industry.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Utility Competition Allowed
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline: Nuclear-Power Plant Troubled

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The U.S. Nuclear Regulatory
 Commission found indications that
operators of the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant hid problems in safety-related software from
regulators.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Nuclear-Power Plant Troubled
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Ross Kerber
Headlines.Headline:
Utility Deregulation Spurs
Marketing Free-for-All

More than
 16,000 New Hampshire residents will get to choose their
electricity supplier later this month, offering the country a glimpse of what's to come with utility
deregulation.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Utility Deregulation Spurs
Marketing Free-for-All
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities said

a federal criminal investigation is underway into the utility's
nuclear-refueling practices, which led to critical findings by
the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission in April.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast Utilities Is Probed
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Northeast Utilities

offered to lower its electric rates by as much as 10% if New
Hampshire regulators agree to delay until the year 2000 a
plan to open competition for customers.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Northeast May Lower Rates
